00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:41.899
So what is Apache Spark?

00:02:41.899 --> 00:02:45.660
It's a fast and general engine for large-scale data processing, right?

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:51.899
So this is, and I want to emphasize the engine part of that, right?

00:02:51.899 --> 00:02:56.899
So this is used to manipulate data at scale.

00:02:56.899 --> 00:03:02.059
This can integrate with the Hadoop ecosystem which is important because, you know, often

00:03:02.059 --> 00:03:07.339
the data that you want to access is already in Hadoop so then the fact that Spark can

00:03:07.339 --> 00:03:11.740
integrate with that ecosystem is extremely important.

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:17.539
It also supports Spark SQL which is basically HiveQL or HQL.

00:03:17.539 --> 00:03:21.419
It has nice built-in machine learning algorithms that we're going to talk about that increase

00:03:21.419 --> 00:03:27.460
the toolkit for analyzing data at scale and it's designed for performance, this was designed

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:32.779
to work interactively with the analyst as opposed to batch processing.

00:03:32.779 --> 00:03:40.300
And finally it's extensible, so you can extend this platform, the Spark platform to include

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:46.300
other modules or custom code or other things that you want to contribute to that ecosystem.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:53.539
So SparklyR, SparklyR is an R package that RStudio built.

00:03:53.539 --> 00:03:58.940
So we, you know, we built it and released it on to CRAN a few weeks ago.

00:03:58.940 --> 00:04:03.100
It's open source, it's free to use, anyone can use it and also mentioned, you know, Spark

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:08.740
and Hadoop are also open source so you have a complete open source stack here if you choose

00:04:08.740 --> 00:04:10.220
to use that.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:16.339
We integrated SparklyR with RStudio IDE.

00:04:16.339 --> 00:04:21.899
We created a new Spark pane that allows you to browse the data and the metadata inside

00:04:21.899 --> 00:04:32.100
of your Spark instance and we've created a dplyr backend with SparklyR as well so that

00:04:32.100 --> 00:04:39.179
you can access, you can use dplyr to do all of your SQL translation on your Spark data

00:04:39.179 --> 00:04:41.140
frames.

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:48.820
Finally we made it extensible so you can plug other things into it like we previously discussed.

00:04:48.820 --> 00:04:54.059
So if you're investing in Spark, if your organization is investing in Spark, there's really nothing

00:04:54.059 --> 00:04:59.140
stopping you from using it with the full power of R and that's my main message to you today

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:04.619
that if your organization is interested in Spark or using Spark, then the R analysts

00:05:04.619 --> 00:05:12.700
